result.execSummary:
On one or more charges, the deferred prosecution or sentencing agreement(s) on this case were canceled, and the charge(s) were dismissed.

The defendant David L Nelson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. David L Nelson is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • David L Nelson was found guilty of Resisting or Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).
  • David L Nelson was found guilty of Possess Drug Paraphernalia, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 961.573(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

ADA Melissa Inlow appeared for the State.  Defendant appeared in person and with Attorney Poss.  Defendant plead no contest to Counts 3 and Count 4.   Diversion agreement on Count 1.  Defendant plead guilty to Count 1.   Count 2 dismissed, but read in for sentencing purposes.   Court recited the charges and possible penalties on the counts he plead to.  Defendant understood.  Court reviewed the plea questionnaire, constitutional rights and elements with the defendant.  Court inquired if the defendant read and understood the diversion agreement on Count 1.  He stated that he read it with Attorney Poss and understood the agreement and can comply with the requirements.  Felony warnings given to the defendant.  Defense stipulated that there is a factual basis for the pleas.   Court found that the defendant freely, voluntarily, knowingly and intelligently entered his plea and waived his constitutional rights.  Court found that a factual basis exists for the plea.  Found guilty of Resisting, contrary to 946.41(1) and Possession of drug paraphernalia, contrary to 961.573(1).  Diversion agreement appoved, finding withheld on Count 1.  Joint recommendation on counts 3 and 4 for:  probation 2 years.    The defendant shall comply with any treatment, evaluations and/or programming as deemed appropriate by a risk and needs assessment and the probation agent.  Defendant must sign any releases agent deems necessary to verify defendant's compliance with probation conditions.  AODA if agent recommends.  s/m employment.  No contact A.H. or S.F. Not to possess any prescription medications of any kind unless those have been prescribed to the defendant by a physician, and in that case, the defendant shall take such medications only as prescribed.
